      Destiny
   =20
 =20

A not uncommon situation is: You are an employee of a hot tech startup, you=
=C2=A0own stock in your startup, but you can=E2=80=99t sell it. One reason =
that you might not be able to sell it is that=C2=A0the company isn=E2=80=99=
t public yet, so the shares aren=E2=80=99t listed on the stock exchange and=
 there is no easy way to sell them. But that problem can be overcome: Peopl=
e want to buy the stocks of hot private startups, there are online marketpl=
aces=C2=A0and brokers looking for shares, and probably with a bit of effort=
 you could find a buyer.
The other reason that you might not be able to sell your stock is that the =
company doesn=E2=80=99t let you. It is pretty common for hot private tech s=
tartups to limit the=C2=A0sale=C2=A0of their stock: The company might have =
transfer restrictions (=E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t sell your stock without o=
ur=C2=A0permission=E2=80=9D), or a right of first refusal=C2=A0(ROFR,=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t sell your stock unless you first offer to sell i=
t back to us at the same price=E2=80=9D), or both. Of course these transfer=
 restrictions will go away when the company goes public, but you don=E2=80=
=99t know when that will be, and it could be a long wait.
