=80=99t do it at the size or price you want, or it=E2=80=99s between buybac=
ks and you want money now.=C2=A0
Meanwhile lots of people want your stock: It=E2=80=99s a hot startup and th=
ere=E2=80=99s plenty of demand. You=E2=80=99d think there=E2=80=99d be a tr=
ade. The trade is:
=09A buyer comes to you and says =E2=80=9CI really want your stock and I=E2=
=80=99ll give you $50 per share.=E2=80=9D=09You say =E2=80=9Cthat sounds gr=
eat, but there are transfer restrictions and I can=E2=80=99t sell until we =
go public.=E2=80=9D=09The buyer says: =E2=80=9CSure, sure, but stock is jus=
t a promise of future cash flows anyway; it=E2=80=99s not like I need the s=
tock certificate today. I just=C2=A0want to pay today=E2=80=99s price for t=
he stock, because I think it will go up.=C2=A0Tell you what: I=E2=80=99ll g=
ive you $50 today, and when the company=C2=A0does=C2=A0go public,=C2=A0then=
=C2=A0you give me the shares.=E2=80=9D
  [2]

=09You say =E2=80=9Csure,=E2=80=9D she gives you the $50, and you write a l=
ittle contract saying =E2=80=9CIOU: startup shares.=E2=80=9D=09Two years la=
ter (or whenever),=C2=A0the company goes public,
  [3]
=C2=A0the transfer restrictions lift, you get your shares, and you deliver =
them to her. If the stock is at $400, you feel a twinge of regret: You=E2=
=80=99re giving her stock worth $400 today, and all you got was $50 two yea=
rs ago.=C2=A0

This is called a =E2=80=9Cforward contract.=E2=80=9D
  [4]
=C2=A0There are some risks:
=09If your company has transfer restrictions, they=C2=A0probably cover forw=
ard contracts. They won=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t sell your =
stock=E2=80=9D; they will say something more complicated like =E2=80=9Cyou =
can=E2=80=99t sell, pledge, assign, agree to sell, enter a derivative contr=
act to sell, etc., etc.=E2=80=9D your stock. The point of a forward contrac=
t is not that it is=C2=A0allowed=C2=A0by your company; the point is that yo=
u can sign the contract now, and deliver the stock later, without your comp=
any=C2=A0knowing about it.=09But say that=C2=A0the company goes public at $=
400 per share, two years after you did the forward contract. You have all t=
his stock worth $400 per share. The buyer comes to you and says =E2=80=9Che=
y, remember me? We had a contract? I paid you $50 per share for your stock?=
 I=E2=80=99d like the stock now.=E2=80=9D You feel a twinge of regret, but =
might you also feel a twinge of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0amnesia? Litigiousness? =E2=
=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t remember any contract,=E2=80=9D you might tell the bu=
yer. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m pretty sure it=E2=80=99s invalid anyway,=E2=80=9D=
 you might add, =E2=80=9Cbecause the company=E2=80=99s transfer restriction=
s cover forward contracts. See you in court!=E2=80=9D=09Say that the compan=
y goes public at $400 per share. The company now=C2=A0has all this extra ca=
sh, and this valuable stock. The=C2=A0company=C2=A0gets wind of your forwar=
d contract. It calls you and/or the buyer and says =E2=80=9Chey, it seems l=
