      SEC v. crypto
   =20
 =20

A pretty standard story in crypto is:
=09Crypto in general, and Crypto Project X in particular, are=C2=A0building=
 something.=C2=A0Each crypto project is working to achieve some vision of=
=C2=A0the future of finance or communications or media or wireless networki=
ng or whatever, and crypto collectively =E2=80=94=C2=A0the aggregate of tho=
se projects =E2=80=94=C2=A0is moving toward some loosely shared vision of a=
 future of decentralized ownership, censorship resistance, etc.=09By buying=
 tokens of Crypto Project X, you are betting on the success of whatever the=
y are building: If the thing succeeds, the tokens will be worth more than y=
ou paid for them.=09
Probably=C2=A0the people building Crypto Project X are=C2=A0selling=C2=A0it=
s tokens to raise money to build the thing, or doing something that rhymes =
with that.
  [5]



This is not the only story in crypto; there is another common story that go=
es like =E2=80=9Csomeone created some tokens as a joke and now they are wor=
th billions of dollars.=E2=80=9D But the one I laid out above is important.=
 For one thing, it describes a lot of big crypto projects. Also, though, it=
 would be hard to=C2=A0care=C2=A0about crypto if it=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=99t try=
ing to build something. =E2=80=9CDogecoin is a joke and if you buy it it mi=
ght go up=E2=80=9D is, I think, a very interesting fact about modern financ=
e, but you=E2=80=99d feel silly devoting your life to it.=C2=A0Read Write O=
wn: Building the Next Era of the Internet=C2=A0is the name of venture capit=
alist Chris Dixon=E2=80=99s book about crypto, and if you are a venture cap=
italist =E2=80=9Cthe next era of the internet=E2=80=9D is a better thing to=
 back than =E2=80=9Ca joke about a dog.=E2=80=9D
The problem with this story, though, is that Crypto Project X=E2=80=99s tok=
ens sure sound like they are securities=C2=A0under US law. A security is =
=E2=80=9Can investment of money in a common enterprise with profits to come=
 solely from the efforts of others,=E2=80=9D and what I laid out above =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Crypto Project X is a group of people building a thing, they ra=
ise money by selling tokens, and you buy tokens hoping to make money if the=
ir thing succeeds =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that.
US securities law exists mostly to prevent swindling in the sale of securit=
ies. This=C2=A0creates several problems for crypto:
=09Some crypto projects are in fact swindles, and securities law is bad for=
 them.=09The main way that the law prevents swindles is by requiring disclo=
sure by securities issuers, and the disclosure rules are not well adapted t=
o crypto, meaning that even a non-swindle crypto project will have a hard t=
ime registering its tokens and complying with US law.=09The law empowers th=
e US Securities and Exchange Commission to regulate securities, and the SEC=
=C2=A0hates=C2=A0crypto and does not do anything to make registration easy =
or even possible.=09Most critically, perhaps, the law also regulates securi=
ties=C2=A0exchanges, and it is hard for a crypto exchange to register with =
the SEC as a securities exchange. So the SEC can go after crypto exchanges =
for illegally listing crypto tokens that are securities.

And the SEC has done that, suing Coinbase Global Inc. and other crypto exch=
anges for operating illegal securities exchanges.
This really is an existential problem for crypto in the US, and the industr=
y=E2=80=99s response has been to argue that these crypto tokens are not sec=
urities. The leading form of this argument goes something like this:
=09A security is an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract,=E2=80=9D and there is no =
contract between=C2=A0you and Crypto Project X. Sure they say they will bui=
ld the project, and you expect them to, and that=E2=80=99s why you invested=
. But you never signed a contract; if they just run off with your money you=
 can=E2=80=99t sue. Therefore, not a security.=09Even if there=C2=A0is some=
 sort of contractual arrangement between you and Crypto Project X, the=C2=
=A0token=C2=A0is not a security. The security is something like =E2=80=9Cth=
e token plus the other arrangements and expectations you have with Crypto P=
roject X.=E2=80=9D But the token is not the contract;=C2=A0the token is =E2=
=80=9Clittle more than [an] alphanumeric cryptographic sequence.=E2=80=9D M=
aybe Crypto Project X issued a security, but=C2=A0secondary market=C2=A0tra=
ding in the token =E2=80=94=C2=A0people buying and selling it on an exchang=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0is not a securities transaction, so crypto exchanges are n=
ot securities exchanges.

I have never found these arguments especially persuasive; to me, these toke=
ns are analogous to stock in companies, and secondary trading in Meta Platf=
orms Inc. stock is obviously a securities transaction even though none of t=
he money goes to Meta. (A share of stock is also, trivially, =E2=80=9Clittl=
e more than an alphanumeric cryptographic sequence,=E2=80=9D an entry in a =
computer database: It=E2=80=99s what the database entry=C2=A0represents=C2=
=A0that makes it a security.)
But last July a federal judge in New York was persuaded, issuing a puzzling=
 ruling in the SEC=E2=80=99s case against Ripple Labs Inc. finding that Rip=
ple=E2=80=99s XRP token is mostly not a security. I thought that perhaps I =
had it all wrong, and crypto tokens really are a get-out-of-securities-law-=
free card: You can raise money for your business by selling quasi-stock and=
 calling it a token, you can do as much fraud as you want, and the SEC can=
=E2=80=99t do anything about it.
Since then, though, the SEC has been on a winning streak against crypto. Sh=
ortly after the Ripple decision, another New York federal judge issued a de=
cision in the SEC=E2=80=99s case against Terraform Labs and its founder Do =
Kwon,=C2=A0finding, no, of course Terra=E2=80=99s tokens are securities. An=
d last month, a different New York federal judge ruled=C2=A0that the SEC=E2=
=80=99s case against Coinbase can go forward: =E2=80=9CThe =E2=80=98crypto=
=E2=80=99 nomenclature may be of recent vintage,=E2=80=9D she wrote,=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cbut the challenged transactions fall comfortably within the framew=
ork that courts have used to identify securities for nearly eighty years.=
=E2=80=9D
Here is her opinion, which strikes me as thorough and=C2=A0straightforward,=
 and which surveys=C2=A0several other cases reaching similar results, more =
or less ignoring the Ripple decision. Coinbase had argued that crypto token=
s were like Beanie Babies: speculative investments, but not speculative inv=
estments=C2=A0in a business. The judge rejected that argument, writing that=
 =E2=80=9Cunlike in the transaction of commodities or collectibles (includi=
ng the Beanie Babies discussed during the oral argument), which may be inde=
pendently consumed or used, a crypto-asset is necessarily intermingled with=
 its digital network =E2=80=94 a network without which no token can exist.=
=E2=80=9D
And then last week the SEC won its jury trial against Terra. The Wall Stree=
t Journal reports:

After a two-week civil trial, a New York jury agreed with the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 claims that Kwon and his firm, Terraform Labs, defrauded investors by misl=
eading them about the stability of TerraUSD, a so-called stablecoin designe=
d to maintain a value of $1. Kwon had claimed that TerraUSD would =E2=80=9C=
self-heal=E2=80=9D if its value ever dropped below the peg.
The decision was the latest in a series of federal court wins bolstering re=
gulators=E2=80=99 efforts to force the freewheeling industry to comply with=
 the same laws that govern the stock and bond markets.=C2=A0

In some sense, the Terra result was obvious once the judge allowed the case=
 to go forward: If you think that Terra=E2=80=99s tokens were=C2=A0securiti=
es, then=C2=A0of course=C2=A0you are going to find that Terra did=C2=A0secu=
rities fraud. This is in part because there is a lot of evidence that Kwon =
and Terraform were lying to investors about=C2=A0important facts of the Ter=
ra ecosystem, but there is also the more straightforward fact that Terra cr=
ashed and incinerated a lot of investor money. If (1) you call a thing a =
=E2=80=9Cstablecoin,=E2=80=9D (2) its value drops to $0.026=C2=A0and (3) it=
 is a security, then (4) you=E2=80=99re going to get sued for securities fr=
aud and (5) you are going to lose.
Or as SEC Enforcement Director Gurbir Grewal put it in a statement after th=
e verdict:
Through these deceptions, the defendants caused devastating losses for inve=
stors and wiped out tens of billions of market value nearly overnight. For =
all of crypto=E2=80=99s promises, the lack of registration and compliance h=
ave very real consequences for real people.
Last year, as the SEC accelerated=C2=A0its crypto crackdown, I wrote about =
its timing. It seemed to me that cracking down on crypto in the wake of a c=
rypto collapse was arguably bad regulation (better to prevent the collapse!=
) but good realpolitik:
In 2021, if the SEC thought your token was a security and you thought it wa=
sn=E2=80=99t, you could go to court to argue about it, and try to convince =
a judge that the SEC was wrong on the law. You might win, who knows. =E2=80=
=A6 But in 2023, the SEC can go to court and say to a judge =E2=80=9Cwe nee=
d to protect investors from unregistered crypto securities offerings, becau=
se look at how many of them are frauds that went bankrupt,=E2=80=9D and whi=
le that legal argument is no better than it was in 2021, it is much more pe=
rsuasive now. At some emotional level the debate is =E2=80=9Cwe need to sto=
p fraudsters=E2=80=9D versus =E2=80=9Cwe need to allow for innovation,=E2=
=80=9D and the fraud/innovation balance has shifted a lot in recent months.
Well, now crypto is booming again, but the memory=C2=A0of all those frauds =
is still pretty fresh, and the SEC has notched some important wins.

