  [1] There are some situations where public companies might have transfer =
restrictions or ROFRs on some of their shares, but generally not permanent =
restrictions for every employee. Employees might find themselves locked up =
for a few months after the initial public offering, and any new grant of sh=
ares might be restricted for some period, but eventually they=E2=80=99ll ha=
ve freely tradable stock.


  [2] Realistically she=E2=80=99d probably pay you less than $50, to accoun=
t for the risk and delay and complexity.


  [3] Or the company is acquired, you get $20 per share in cash, and the fo=
rward contract requires you to pay her the $20. Or the company fails, the s=
tock is worth $0, and the forward contract doesn=E2=80=99t matter.=20


  [4] Generically, a =E2=80=9Cforward contract=E2=80=9D often means a contr=
act in which (1) I agree to pay you $50 in a year and (2) you agree to deli=
ver me the stock in a year. The thing in the text is a =E2=80=9Cprepaid for=
ward contract,=E2=80=9D in which I pay you now and you deliver the stock la=
ter. But in tech-startup employee liquidity usage, a =E2=80=9Cforward contr=
act=E2=80=9D is normally prepaid, because you want the money now.


  [5] E.g., they are building the thing on the cheap without raising money,=
 but they *have* a lot of the tokens, and if the thing succeeds those token=
s will make them rich.


