<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A not uncommon situation is: You are an employ=
ee of a hot tech startup, you=C2=A0own stock in your startup, but you can=
=E2=80=99t sell it. One reason that you might not be able to sell it is tha=
t=C2=A0the company isn=E2=80=99t public yet, so the shares aren=E2=80=99t l=
isted on the stock exchange and there is no easy way to sell them. But that=
 problem can be overcome: People want to buy the stocks of hot private star=
tups, there are online marketplaces=C2=A0and brokers looking for shares, an=
d probably with a bit of effort you could find a buyer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other reason that you might not be able to=
 sell your stock is that the company doesn=E2=80=99t let you. It is pretty =
common for hot private tech startups to limit the=C2=A0sale<em>=C2=A0</em>o=
f their stock: The company might have transfer restrictions (=E2=80=9Cyou c=
an=E2=80=99t sell your stock without our=C2=A0permission=E2=80=9D), or a ri=
ght of first refusal=C2=A0(ROFR,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t sell your =
stock unless you first offer to sell it back to us at the same price=E2=80=
=9D), or both. Of course these transfer restrictions will go away when the =
company goes public, but you don=E2=80=99t know when that will be, and it c=
ould be a long wait.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And so even if you find a buyer, you can=E2=80=99t sell=C2=A0to h=
er without going to the company for permission. And the company might well =
say no: Those restrictions exist so that the company can control its shareh=
older base, and it doesn=E2=80=99t want just anyone to own its stock. It wa=
nts you to own the stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you might prefer money: Perhaps your start=
up has been private for a long time, its valuation is high, you=E2=80=99d l=
ike a new house, and you=E2=80=99d like to cash out a bit now. Often, these=
 days, mature private=C2=A0tech startups recognize this problem and periodi=
cally <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259=
352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItMDc=
vb3BlbmFpLXdhcy1wcmV0dHktcG9ydGFibGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQwODI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDA4JnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa2a53504" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">buy =
back stock</a> from employees. But perhaps your company doesn=E2=80=99t do =
that, or it doesn=E2=80=99t do it at the size or price you want, or it=E2=
=80=99s between buybacks and you want money now.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile lots of people want your stock: It=
=E2=80=99s a hot startup and there=E2=80=99s plenty of demand. You=E2=80=99=
d think there=E2=80=99d be a trade. The trade is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A buyer comes to you and says =E2=80=
=9CI really want your stock and I=E2=80=99ll give you $50 per share.=E2=80=
=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You say =E2=80=9Cthat sounds g=
reat, but there are transfer restrictions and I can=E2=80=99t sell until we=
 go public.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The buyer say=
s: =E2=80=9CSure, sure, but stock is just a promise of future cash flows an=
yway; it=E2=80=99s not like I need the stock certificate today. I just=C2=
=A0want to pay today=E2=80=99s <em>price </em>for the stock, because I thin=
k it will go up<em>.</em>=C2=A0Tell you what: I=E2=80=99ll give you $50 tod=
ay, and when the company=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>go public,=C2=A0<em>then=
=C2=A0</em>you give me the shares.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You say =E2=80=9Csure,=E2=80=9D s=
he gives you the $50, and you write a little contract saying =E2=80=9CIOU: =
startup shares.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Two years=
 later (or whenever),=C2=A0the company goes public,<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0the transfer restrictions lift, you get your shares, and you deli=
ver them to her. If the stock is at $400, you feel a twinge of regret: You=
=E2=80=99re giving her stock worth $400 today, and all you got was $50 two =
years ago.=C2=A0</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly9tZWRpdW0uY2=
9tL0Bqb25hdGhhbi5sb25zZGFsZS90aGUtbWFueS1wcm9ibGVtcy13aXRoLWZvcndhcmQtcHVyY=
2hhc2UtY29udHJhY3RzLTQ4ODg1NWM2OWU0Mg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9eb42b91" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">forward contract</a>.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There are some risks:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If your company has transfer restrict=
ions, they=C2=A0<em>probably cover forward contracts</em>. They won=E2=80=
=99t say =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t sell your stock=E2=80=9D; they will say=
 something more complicated like =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t sell, pledge, a=
ssign, agree to sell, enter a derivative contract to sell, etc., etc.=E2=80=
=9D your stock. The point of a forward contract is not that it is=C2=A0<em>=
allowed=C2=A0</em>by your company; the point is that you can sign the contr=
act now, and deliver the stock later, without your company=C2=A0<em>knowing=
 about it</em>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But say that=C2=A0=
the company goes public at $400 per share, two years after you did the forw=
ard contract. You have all this stock worth $400 per share. The buyer comes=
 to you and says =E2=80=9Chey, remember me? We had a contract? I paid you $=
50 per share for your stock? I=E2=80=99d like the stock now.=E2=80=9D You f=
eel a twinge of regret, but might you also feel a twinge of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=
amnesia? Litigiousness? =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t remember any contract,=E2=
=80=9D you might tell the buyer. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m pretty sure it=E2=80=
=99s invalid anyway,=E2=80=9D you might add, =E2=80=9Cbecause the company=
=E2=80=99s transfer restrictions cover forward contracts. See you in court!=
=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Say that the company goe=
s public at $400 per share. The <em>company</em> now=C2=A0has all this extr=
a cash, and this valuable stock. The=C2=A0<em>company=C2=A0</em>gets wind o=
f your forward contract. It calls you and/or the buyer and says =E2=80=9Che=
y, it seems like you agreed to trade this stock at $50 two years ago. Well,=
 we had a right of first refusal, and we are now exercising it, so you have=
 to sell=C2=A0<em>us=C2=A0</em>the stock. Today, for $50.=E2=80=9D Your buy=
er =E2=80=94=C2=A0who paid $50 two years ago as a bet that the company woul=
d be far more valuable when it went public, and was right=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0now has to give the stock back and get=C2=A0back only her $50.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One more point about forward contracts. A forw=
ard contract is, in essence, a placeholder for stock, an empty box that wil=
l one day hold a share of stock of the underlying startup. The buyer paid m=
oney for it, because it is desirable. She can=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>it, t=
oo. If she no longer likes the company, or if the company=E2=80=99s valuati=
on has gone up and she wants to take profits, there=E2=80=99s probably some=
 <em>other</em> investor=C2=A0who wants exposure to a hot startup and who w=
ill pay her $60 or whatever for that forward. Maybe that investor will turn=
 around and sell it, too. In two years, when your company goes public, you =
might get a call from a total stranger saying =E2=80=9Chey, you don=E2=80=
=99t know me, but I bought a forward from someone who bought it from someon=
e who bought it from someone who bought it from someone who bought it from =
you, so please send me the stock.=E2=80=9D Your twinge of amnesia might be =
strong.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the New York Times last Friday, <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wNC8wNS90ZWNobm9sb2d5L2ludmVzdC1wcml2YXRlLXRlY2gt=
b3BlbmFpLXNwYWNleC5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f22c2b7" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Erin Gr=
iffith had a fun article</a> about Destiny Tech100, a=C2=A0publicly traded =
closed-end fund=C2=A0that invests in private tech startups:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is offering a publicly traded fund that con=
tains shares of 23 private tech companies including Stripe, SpaceX, OpenAI,=
 Discord and Epic Games. The fund, which began trading on the New York Stoc=
k Exchange last week, plans to expand its holdings to include stock in 100 =
start-ups.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sohail Prasad, the chief executive of Destiny =
XYZ, the parent company of the fund, said his goal was to let anyone own pa=
rt of the tech industry=E2=80=99s top private companies. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Prasad and a team of five deal makers have=
 used their relationships to get access to the start-up shares that Destiny=
 has bought so far. Private companies can be picky about whom they let own =
their shares. But as they stay private for longer, their employees and earl=
y investors can become antsy to cash out. The most valuable companies have =
held regular =E2=80=9Ctender offers=E2=80=9D that allow employees to sell t=
heir shares, which is one way Destiny Tech100 buys stock.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a fascinating model: It trades publicly=
=C2=A0on the New York Stock Exchange (under the ticker DXYZ), but its inves=
tments are private and illiquid. It <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZ=
Gdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTU3NTg3MjIzMDAxOTI0L2VzMDg2XzQyNGIzLmh0bSNwcm9f=
MTA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb57c1b4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">computes its net asset value=
 quarterly</a>, and its <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhL=
zE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTE0NTU0OTI0MDE1OTk0L3hzbEZvcm1OLUNFTl9YMDEvcHJpbWFyeV9kb2Mu=
eG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d4ea28e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">most recent computation</a>=
 lists its net asset value per share at $4.84. It <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTU3NTg3MjI0MDAwMjg3L2VzMTA1XzQ5N2=
FkLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcfe023a2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">went public last month<=
/a> with a reference price of $4.84, but started trading at $8.25 and went =
up from there; it closed on Friday at $59.20, and it was trading around $80=
 at noon today. It has a net asset value=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0its computatio=
n of the fair value of its underlying startup stakes =E2=80=94=C2=A0of abou=
t <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTE0NTU=
0OTI0MDE1OTk0L3hzbEZvcm1OLUNFTl9YMDEvcHJpbWFyeV9kb2MueG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cC6d4ea28e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">$54 million</a>, and=C2=A0a market=C2=A0capitaliz=
ation =E2=80=94=C2=A0the value that the market places on its shares =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0of about $875 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Somebody is wrong! One way to model this is th=
at there is $875 million of demand from regular public investors to own sha=
res in hot private startups, and so far only about $54 million of supply. B=
ut if each of this fund=E2=80=99s holdings goes up 1,000% by the time they =
go public, people who bought into the fund today will=C2=A0<em>lose money</=
em>. Weird!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other weird thing is, as Griffith reports:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fund has also bought shares in Stripe and =
Plaid, a financial technology provider, through =E2=80=9Cforward contracts.=
=E2=80=9D In these agreements, start-up employees can get cash by agreeing =
to transfer their company shares to an investor when the company goes publi=
c or sells.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The contracts are controversial. Stripe has sa=
id that it forbids its current and former employees to strike such deals an=
d that any forward contract is void. Mr. Prasad said his fund was confident=
 the deals were legal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdXBwb3J0LnN0cmlwZS5jb20vcXVl=
c3Rpb25zL3N0cmlwZS1mb3J3YXJkLWNvbnRyYWN0cy1hbmQtb3RoZXItdW5hdXRob3JpemVkLWx=
pcXVpZGl0eS10cmFuc2FjdGlvbnM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5a67d6e" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Str=
ipe=E2=80=99s threat</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be clear, transactions in which=
 a Stripe [employee] receives payment now and promises to transfer shares d=
irectly or indirectly in the future are subject to ROFRs and transfer restr=
ictions. This means, among other things, that at the time the transaction i=
s =E2=80=9Cclosed out=E2=80=9D Stripe is entitled to step in and repurchase=
 the shares that are subject to the contract at the original price paid by =
the buyer. We intend to vigorously enforce our ROFR rights with respect to =
all such contracts.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be fair, Destiny Tech100 <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Vj=
Lmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTU3NTg3MjIzMDAxOTI0L2VzMDg=
2XzQyNGIzLmh0bSNwcm9fMDM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a56dbc9" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">lists</=
a> its investment in Stripe forward contracts as having a cost of about $3.=
5 million and a fair value (as of last June) of about $1 million: It bought=
 into Stripe forwards at the peak, Stripe=E2=80=99s valuation <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcvc3RyaXBlLWZvdW5kZXJzLX=
NoZWQtYmlsbGlvbnMtaW4tcGFpbmZ1bC1zaGlmdC10by1sZWFuZXItdGltZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEM=
DQwODI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXIm=
dXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNDA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB424ec236" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">has fallen</a>, and at this point it would be=C2=A0<em=
>great=C2=A0</em>for the fund if Stripe tried to buy back its shares at the=
 original price it paid. Still the fund=E2=80=99s forward-related <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTU3NTg3MjIzMDAx=
OTI0L2VzMDg2XzQyNGIzLmh0bSNwcm9fMDU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb5a5dd5b" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">risk factors</a> are a fun read:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Should counterparties breach their agreement i=
nadvertently, by operation of law, intentionally, or fraudulently, it could=
 affect our performance. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In cases where we purchase a forward contract =
through a secondary marketplace, we may have no direct relationship with, o=
r right to contact, enforce rights against, or obtain personal information =
or contact information concerning the counterparty(ies). ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Should the portfolio company object to the exi=
stence of the forward contract, it may take any number of steps to discoura=
ge or obstruct the transactions, including claiming that the counterparty t=
ransactions violate the portfolio company=E2=80=99s agreements, claiming ca=
uses of action against counterparties or us, defensive measures intended to=
 discourage counterparties from selling the portfolio company=E2=80=99s sec=
urities to us, refusing to accept or process securities transfers, or claim=
ing rights to rescind our transactions or trigger rights of refusal to purc=
hase the portfolio company=E2=80=99s securities involved in our transaction=
s.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It seems to me that the safest way for a forwa=
rd contract to work is for the company=C2=A0<em>not to know about it:=C2=A0=
</em>Once it goes public, the seller just delivers the unrestricted stock a=
nd never tells the company. But once you put it in a prospectus, the compan=
y knows!</p>
