tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">the Financial Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street banks have warned that their next =
wave of hiring in France may be stunted without restrictions on dismissal c=
osts for highly paid traders, a flagship measure that has been left out of =
a reform package intended to bolster Paris as a financial centre. =E2=80=A6=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Redundancy payouts to traders earning more tha=
n =E2=82=AC1mn a year in Paris can end up being more than five times that o=
f London, although there is less of a difference between France and the res=
t of Europe. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea under review would be to put more spe=
cific limits on payouts to traders so they don=E2=80=99t exceed a threshold=
 of about half a million euros. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Alexandre Holroyd, a lawmaker who is leading t=
he reform package, said France=E2=80=99s labour rules were meant to be prot=
ective, but had never been designed to overcompensate traders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CA trading floor is somewhere where th=
ere is a lot of volatility and variations in headcount,=E2=80=9D Holroyd sa=
id. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s the flipside of being paid sums of money that are=
 completely disproportionate to more than 99 per cent of people.=E2=80=9D</=
p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you hire a trader and pay her more than a m=
illion euros a year, and she doesn=E2=80=99t work out, you=E2=80=99d like t=
o be able to get rid of her without paying her millions more. On the other =
hand, if you=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>a trader getting paid more than a milli=
on euros a year, and your bank decides to get rid of you,=C2=A0<em>you=E2=
=80=99d </em>like to get paid millions more, no? Seems nicer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also there are risk-management considerations;=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34967840.259352/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZGlmZi5jby9hcmNoaXZlL3RoZS1kYXRhLWJ1c2luZXNzLWF0LXRocmVl=
LXJlc29sdXRpb25zLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53eba40b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Byrne Hobart =
notes</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">High legally-mandated payouts for =
firing amount to a put option on their compensation. If they get a free put=
 option, their incentive is to take more risk. Part of what banks are worri=
ed about is what it costs to fire an underperforming trader, but another th=
ing it's prudent for them to worry about is how much it pays for a trader t=
o underperform.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is true as a matter of options math, but =
I wonder how true it is sociologically. Are French traders notably riskier =
than British or American ones? (There are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
